<subSubSection id="2E0938FB10DB27456A689CDD44D23A1A" pageId="19" pageNumber="142" type="comments">
<paragraph id="E2D2963FDBF85139DC9E2B8AA09A19D4" pageId="19" pageNumber="142">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="49FB7E776D937CA99E3F8066C3ACDD4F" pageId="19" pageNumber="142">
<taxonomicName id="9281BEAF4FFD7434033D8C36FFCAB55F" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Muhlenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Muhlenbergia ciliata" order="Poales" pageId="19" pageNumber="142" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliata">
<emphasis id="C624D9544CCD2EE530430AD2EB0024EA" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="142">Muhlenbergia ciliata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName id="FE63FB8A48E41CCF31A92CE69C2F9E78" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. romaschenkoi" order="Poales" pageId="19" pageNumber="142" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="romaschenkoi">
<emphasis id="8B12C23A4941EAC29AE02DB767712270" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="142">M. romaschenkoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and can be differentiated from the latter in having short ligules 0.2-0.8 mm long [1.2-3.0 (-5.0) mm long in 
<taxonomicName id="85DF91AD42D10023B8856FB987C858FA" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. romaschenkoi" order="Poales" pageId="19" pageNumber="142" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="romaschenkoi">
<emphasis id="AE63BC2255BD8EC7557B8E16F1D40BA8" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="142">M. romaschenkoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
], paleas that are glabrous between the veins on the proximal 
<normalizedToken id="4F39F1AC1850135A8BFFD9FAE7C3CAE3" originalValue="½">1/2</normalizedToken>
(versus appressed pubescent), 6-13 nodes along the panicle (versus 15-23) and 
<emphasis id="29B9D0A17678B09A1879189086314A5D" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="142">panicles</emphasis>
that are 4-12 cm long (versus 7-15 cm long) [
<bibRefCitation id="B43BC7549625E3187FB2BA12A33328F1" author="Peterson, PM" journalOrPublisher="Caldasia" pageId="58" pageNumber="181" pagination="21 - 54" refId="B28" refString="Peterson, PM, Giraldo-Canas, D, 2011. Las especies de Muhlenbergia (Poaceae: Chloridoideae) de Argentina. Caldasia 33: 21 - 54" title="Las especies de Muhlenbergia (Poaceae: Chloridoideae) de Argentina." volume="33" year="2011">
Peterson and 
<normalizedToken id="99735B792D97FDFB9FEBC3528851C3D9" originalValue="Giraldo-Cañas">Giraldo-Canas</normalizedToken>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="133B4DB26AF97355275A1188AF47D276" author="Peterson, PM" journalOrPublisher="Caldasia" pageId="58" pageNumber="181" refId="B29" refString="Peterson, PM, Giraldo-Canas, D, 2012. Muhlenbergia Schreb. In: Zuloaga FO, Rugolo ZE, Anton AMR (Eds) Flora Argentina, Flora Vascular de la Republica Argentina, Vol. 3, Tomo 1, Monocotyledoneae, Poaceae: Aristidoideae a Pharoideae. IBODA-IMBIV, CONICET, Buenos Aires, Argentina, 140-154." title="Muhlenbergia Schreb. In: Zuloaga FO, Rugolo ZE, Anton AMR (Eds) Flora Argentina, Flora Vascular de la Republica Argentina, Vol. 3, Tomo 1, Monocotyledoneae, Poaceae: Aristidoideae a Pharoideae. IBODA-IMBIV, CONICET, Buenos Aires, Argentina, 140 - 154." year="2012">2012</bibRefCitation>
]. Some individuals of 
<taxonomicName id="2D8C55AB0CE0FBA467BBF57EAEFA1E7B" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. ciliata" order="Poales" pageId="19" pageNumber="142" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="ciliata">
<emphasis id="3513821A87F161073979EF99C7DBE253" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="142">M. ciliata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Peru do not have prominent cilia along the lateral veins that are present in most individuals from North America.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BF6641153E721DF4B6FD5CF11C18DEB9" pageId="19" pageNumber="142">
<taxonomicName id="9061964E9EB9D9CD32EB659964C83628" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Muhlenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Muhlenbergia ciliata" order="Poales" pageId="19" pageNumber="142" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliata">
<emphasis id="31BEED35BE6CD7973FA62DF1CE408316" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="142">Muhlenbergia ciliata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="290AE9889AFABBD4A2F5BA4979EBFDD4" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. pectinata" order="Poales" pageId="19" pageNumber="142" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="pectinata">
<emphasis id="B9EEA3F006F3FB22B2F392A93497C205" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="142">M. pectinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
C.O. Goodd. (North America) and 
<taxonomicName id="C10611D489EA8A0D2A00C1A537D18BE9" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. tenella" order="Poales" pageId="19" pageNumber="142" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="tenella">
<emphasis id="1F2DE2470DF952103727AC0FC8189259" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="142">M. tenella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Kunth) Trin. (North America, Central America and Colombia) [
<bibRefCitation id="FE14B62519F40BD64E4404245BDB8917" DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/25027794" author="Peterson, PM" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany Monographs" pageId="58" pageNumber="181" pagination="1 - 109" refId="B25" refString="Peterson, PM, Annable, CR, 1991. Systematics of the annual species of Muhlenbergia (Poaceae - Eragrostideae). Systematic Botany Monographs 31: 1 - 109, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/25027794" title="Systematics of the annual species of Muhlenbergia (Poaceae - Eragrostideae)." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/25027794" volume="31" year="1991">Peterson and Annable 1991</bibRefCitation>
]. These three species form a clade in 
<taxonomicName id="011A89EF8546338E8A2EE38F44D61A43" authority="subg. Muhlenbergia" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Muhlenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" infraspecific-rank="subg." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Muhlenbergia" order="Poales" pageId="19" pageNumber="142" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus" subGenus="Muhlenbergia">Muhlenbergia subg. Muhlenbergia</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="77084A0AD2A19B6940806479B930EDAD" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3732/ajb.0900359" author="Peterson, PM" journalOrPublisher="American Journal of Botany" pageId="59" pageNumber="182" pagination="1532 - 1554" refId="B38" refString="Peterson, PM, Romaschenko, K, Johnson, G, 2010b. A phylogeny and classification of the Muhlenbergiinae (Poaceae: Chloridoideae: Cynodonteae) based on plastid and nuclear DNA sequences. American Journal of Botany 97 (9): 1532 - 1554, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3732/ajb.0900359" title="A phylogeny and classification of the Muhlenbergiinae (Poaceae: Chloridoideae: Cynodonteae) based on plastid and nuclear DNA sequences." url="https://doi.org/10.3732/ajb.0900359" volume="97" year="2010 b">Peterson et al. 2010b</bibRefCitation>
; Fig. 
<figureCitation id="1184A8A81A3E78FE1A65182D29596CEC" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A, B Maximum-likelihood tree inferred from combined plastid (ndhA intron, rps 16 - trnK, rps 16 intron, rps 3, and rpl 32 - trnL) and ITS sequences. Thick branches indicate posterior probabilities of 0.95 - 1; species in red occur in South America; scale bar = 2 %." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.114.28799.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/254042" pageId="19" pageNumber="142">1B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
